I rejected a pull request last Tuesday.
The developer had three years of Angular on his resume.
The code told me a different story.
Not because it was broken. It worked. Every button clicked, every API call returned. But the code was quietly screaming something else, and every senior on my team could hear it.
Here is the uncomfortable truth nobody says out loud in code reviews: working code is not the bar. It is the floor.
I have reviewed hundreds of Angular pull requests over the last six years. The same seven mistakes show up again and again, and they instantly tell me where a developer is in their journey. The good news? Every single one takes less than a day to fix.
Let us go through them. Honestly. No lectures, just the mistakes, the fixes, and the actual numbers from my own apps.
Mistake 1: Subscribing Everywhere, Unsubscribing Nowhere
This is the number one memory leak factory in Angular apps, and I see it in almost every junior codebase.
The problem:
export class OrdersComponent implements OnInit {
orders: Order[] = []; constructor(private api: OrderService) {} ngOnInit() {
this.api.getOrders().subscribe(data => {
this.orders = data;
});
